<ITEM>2. <HI>Summary</HI> of the ancient <HI>Virginia;</HI> and of the <HI>Dutch</HI> and <HI>Swede's</HI> preten&s;ions to what was called <HI>New Netherland</HI> by the former, and <HI>New Swedeland</HI> by the latter:&mdash;With a &s;ketch of the fir&s;t &s;ettlement, government and revolutions of the&s;e people on the <HI>Delaware</HI> bay and river;&mdash;Including &s;ome account of the <HI>Maryland</HI> grant to the Lord Baltimore, in 1632; and of the reduction of the <HI>Dutch</HI> and <HI>Swedes</HI> under the Briti&s;h government in 1664.</ITEM>
<ITEM>3. Fir&s;t ri&s;e of <HI>New-Jer&s;ey,</HI> in 1664; and &s;ome account of the En|gli&s;h admini&s;tration by the governors of <HI>N. York,</HI> over the country on <HI>Delaware,</HI> till it was retaken by the <HI>Dutch,</HI> in 1673;&mdash;and of the go|vernment there, after it was &s;urrendered to <HI>England.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM>4. Divi&s;ion of <HI>New-Jer&s;ey</HI> into <HI>Ea&s;t</HI> and <HI>We&s;t New-Jer&s;ey,</HI> in 1676; whereby <HI>W. Penn</HI> fir&s;t became concerned in the latter;&mdash;With a &s;um|mary of the fir&s;t &s;ettlement and public tran&s;actions of <HI>We&s;t New-Jer&s;ey,</HI> by the <HI>Quakers,</HI> &amp;c. continued from the divi&s;ion of the province, in 1676, till about the time of <HI>W. Penn's</HI> obtaining the grant of <HI>Penn&s;yl|vania,</HI> in 1681, &amp;c.</ITEM>
